<br>
First and foremost there are no innocent civilians.  Civilians are aligned with a &quot;side&quot; in the conflict and provide economic support for the war machine that acts on their behalf.  This shouldn't be an alarming revelation.  The United States waged war upon the civilian populace of Germany during World War II.  The desired result was a reduction of economic capacity for Germany to wage war.<br>
<br>
It is my belief that when a country's populace decides war is an easy solution, they should be aware that they themselves are open to the effects of war -- not just the people hired to wage war on their behalf.  The United States populace as a whole does not comprehend exactly how devastating a war can be.  It seems surgical, clean, exact, pin-point, quick, and sanitary.  War is none of these things.<br>
<br>
I have no problem with &quot;an enemy combatant&quot;  being killed during the course of armed combat.  Whether they are killed with nerve gas or a high velocity projectile is irrellevant.  Both can be horrible and slow deaths.<br>
<br>
When &quot;an enemy combatant&quot; is taken prisoner and subjected to the laws of a country, then the country with the prisoner has immediately acknowledged the prisoner has rights.  In the United States, the &quot;inalienable rights&quot; is the minimum level of rights are what the &quot;enemy combatant&quot; has been recognized to have.<br>
<br>
By simply trying to validate the removal of these rights, using any court system under the guidance and jurisdiction of the United States (civil, criminal, military), the United States has ACKNODLEGED that the prisoner at one point in time DID have some form of rights to begin with.<br>
<br>
What is the point of &quot;trying&quot; someone for a crime, with the end result being a removal of rights -- unless the prisoner already had these &quot;inalienable rights&quot;?  Why not just drag them out and summarily execute them instead?  What is the point of pretending to remove rights and privileges, if there were in fact no rights or privileges to remove in the first place? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tuvanvaz>TuvanVaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 608<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/13/03 1:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=86.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Conspiracy Theory</span><hr size=1> Herder, <br>
