As to the Isreal-Palestine thing:  Both sides are at fault.  However, I'm not about to trust the PLO which has renegged on its promise to reject any and all forms of terrorism.  Yasser Arafat is a two-faced opportunist who caters his message to his audience;  If he's talking to his own people, its all about martyrdom and suicide bombers being the best thing since hummus.  If, however, he's talking to anyone else, he condemns terrorism and says Isreal is hindering his efforts to police the Palestinian Authority and crack down on terrorist groups.<br>
<br>
The PLO is rife with corruption and cronieism.  Hamas and the other Islamist movements have set themselves up as genuine charities that provide needed services to the Palestinians, so cracking down on their terrorist wings is virtually impossible to do without a massive loss of popularity...and that's something Arafat would never allow, seemingly even if it meant a real lasting peace.<br>
<br>
Hamas recently offered to suspend suicide bombings against civilians if Isreal agreed to suspend its targetted assassinations.  The Hamas representative said &quot;We will stop killing thier babies if they stop killing ours&quot;.  Sounds good, right?  Wait, there's a catch: they would still continue to attack soldiers.  This is not a real negiotiation; they are offering something thay know Isreal will never accept.<br>
<br>
Keep in mind, Isreal was founded with a UN mandate (one that the United States didn't particularly care for).  In fact, the first military supporters of Isreal (militarily) were in fact Britain and France.  Only later did the US/Isreal friendship blossom (Egypt's President Nasr and his pan-Arab pro-Soviet idealism helped a lot here).<br>
<br>
Is Isreal an innocent babe?  Hell no.  There's blood on their hands as well.  They haven't exactly been the best allies at times, but they have a  record of keeping their promises much better then the PLO's cult of personality around Arafat.<br>
